00:00:00.770 --> 00:00:07.550
Let's say I have some
transformation from R2 to R2.

00:00:07.550 --> 00:00:11.280
And it's essentially just a
multiplication times a matrix.

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:13.220
And we know that all linear
transformations can be

00:00:13.220 --> 00:00:16.260
expressed as a multiplication
of a matrix, but this one is

00:00:16.260 --> 00:00:25.940
equal to the matrix 1, 3, 2, 6
times whatever vector you give

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:27.170
me in my domain.

00:00:27.170 --> 00:00:30.590
Times x1, x2.

00:00:30.590 --> 00:00:35.030
Now let's say I have some
subset in my codomain.

00:00:35.030 --> 00:00:36.550
So let me draw this
right here.

00:00:36.550 --> 00:00:39.350
So my domain looks like that.

00:00:39.350 --> 00:00:41.310
It's R2.

00:00:41.310 --> 00:00:44.840
And of course my function or
my transformation maps

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:48.340
elements of R2 into elements
of its codomain which also

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:50.100
happens to be R2.

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:52.310
I could show it mapping into
itself, but for the sake of

00:00:52.310 --> 00:00:55.150
simplicity let's draw
my codomain here.

00:00:55.150 --> 00:00:57.590
And our transformation of course
maps, for any element

00:00:57.590 --> 00:01:01.215
here, the transformation of that
will be an association or

00:01:01.215 --> 00:01:03.560
a mapping into R2.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:10.970
Now what if we take some subset
of R2, and let's just

00:01:10.970 --> 00:01:15.650
say it's a set of two vectors,
the zero vector in R2, and the

00:01:15.650 --> 00:01:18.800
vector 1, 2.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:20.840
So it's literally, let's
say it's this point.

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:22.070
Let me do it in a
different color.

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:26.110
Let's say this is my
zero vector in R2.

00:01:26.110 --> 00:01:26.920
I'm not plotting them.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:30.350
I'm just showing that they're
in this, they're in R2.

00:01:30.350 --> 00:01:32.430
That's my zero vector,
and let's say the

00:01:32.430 --> 00:01:35.170
vector 1,2 is here.

00:01:35.170 --> 00:01:36.370
1,2.

00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:40.050
What I want to know is, what are
all of the vectors in my

00:01:40.050 --> 00:01:45.570
domain whose transformations
map to this subset?

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:46.670
Map to this point?

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:49.780
So I want to know, I'm
essentially, I want to know

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:51.840
the preimage of S.

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:54.730
So the preimage of S, let
me be careful, the

00:01:54.730 --> 00:02:04.450
preimage of S under T.

00:02:04.450 --> 00:02:07.160
And I said be careful because
when you say preimage of

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:10.360
something without saying under
something else, it implies

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:10.930
that you're taking.

00:02:10.930 --> 00:02:13.580
Well when you say image of
something, it implies you're

00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:15.520
taking the image of an entire
transformation like I showed

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:17.370
you, I think, two videos ago.

00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:19.720
But when you're taking the image
or preimage of a set,

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:23.270
you make sure you say under
what transformation.

00:02:23.270 --> 00:02:26.630
So we want to know the preimage
