00:14:11.890 --> 00:14:14.040
And we're saying, what are all
of the x's that when you

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:20.750
transform them you get
the zero vector?

00:14:20.750 --> 00:14:24.810
And so this idea, this blue
thing right here, it's called

00:14:24.810 --> 00:14:30.570
the kernel of T.

00:14:30.570 --> 00:14:34.880
Sometimes it's written just
shorthand K-E-R of T.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:38.450
And this literally is all of the
vectors that if you apply

00:14:38.450 --> 00:14:40.630
the transformation, let
me write it this way.

00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:46.850
It's all of the vectors in our
domain, which was R2, such

00:14:46.850 --> 00:14:52.940
that the transformation of those
vectors is equal to the

00:14:52.940 --> 00:14:53.620
zero vector.

00:14:53.620 --> 00:14:56.540
There this is the definition
of the kernel.

00:14:56.540 --> 00:15:03.580
And if the transformation is
equal to some matrix times

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:05.670
some vector, and we know that
any linear transformation can

00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:12.460
be written as a matrix vector
product, then the kernel of T

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:16.790
is the same thing as the
null space of A.

00:15:16.790 --> 00:15:18.600
And we saw that earlier
in the video.

